segments.text: There were five states that they were the regional veterinary school for.
I think it was five, Mississippi, Alabama, actually Mississippi, Tennessee, Kentucky, and Florida.
Particularly.
Thank you.
We had a strange class.
They were older.
Nearly all of them had been in World War II.
They had been in military service.
All of them except one were 4F people that couldn't qualify.
That's all, the locker room conversation and everything was where they were going to go to practice and how much money they were going to make.
This is at Iowa State.
What about the Aggies here, their work habits, their liberal or conservative attitudes, their background?
Even at first class, that first class that I taught in 1960, full class I taught in 1966,
Probably there's at least 20 or 25 out of that class that have made tremendous marks in veterinary medicine.
And there were at least a half a dozen or more in the class that graduated in August of 1965 who did equally as well.
There are really some great students in there.
The problem they had then was exercising it.
They got out just at the right time when veterinary medicine began to blossom into the great science that it is.
Instead of being animal treaters, they became scientists.
And many of them have really made tremendous achievements in it.
Dewey Kramer.
for example, here at Texas A&M, was in the first class I taught in 1966.
He got his PhD in December of 1965 and his Doctor of Veterinary Medicine in August of 66.
And he is, of course, he was the first one to do an embryo transplant at the research station in San Antonio.
And several others in that class, Gerald Bratton, Dean Gage,
James Anderson.
It just goes on and on and on.
Men who really made tremendous marks in the veterinary profession.
It's just gotten better every year.
The American Veterinary Medical Association employed an outfit in Chicago to do a study on the profession of veterinary medicine.
And they paid them a rather tidy sum for doing it.
And they came up with the dramatic and marvelous conclusion that by 1985, we would be super-saturated with veterinarians.
And this really had a telling impact on, particularly on those schools who were pumping legislators for money.
They got this little report that says you're going to have too many of them in 1985, as it is.
Well, it turned out they were 100% wrong.
And I said at the time, I don't understand your thinking when here are a group of graduates who represent the upper probably 10% of the academic community as far as academic ability is concerned.
And you're telling me that these people are going to remain unemployed while people of lesser quality are going to be employed?
Let's kid ourselves.
And they've proven it by branching out into so many different directions in the medical profession and are able to hold their own and have held their own.
In some of the early days of DeBakey's transplant work in Houston, a guy named, I can't think of his last name, he's still on the faculty at Tufts, did all the work.
He was an Ohio State graduate that
So they've really made such a tremendous contribution and we're still struggling because the pharmaceutical profession or the pharmaceutical industry and the medical profession too can't afford yet
the studies that need to be done on the so-called exotic animals.
The money isn't there.
And yet in these animals are things that we really need to know and would like to know if we could get the funds and the research facilities to study them.
The San Diego Zoo has done a lot, but they haven't had the opportunity to do it near enough.
Before you got here,
what had you heard about Aggies and Texas A&M?
Based on what you had heard, what were you anticipating?
The only preface I had to coming here was two weeks at a poultry inspection school in Kansas City, Missouri, in January of 1958.
There were two Aggies.
that were there that day.
And I learned a great deal about the people they didn't like in the veterinary faculty here, and little else.
And the only thing else I knew about Texas A&M when I came here in the summer of 65 was, I can't think of his last name, the high jumper that got the bronze medal in 52.
And Randy Mattson and John Kimbrough.
The disaster in the Texas game in 63, which I was watching on television that day.
But other than that, I didn't... Had you heard about Aggie tradition?
No, no, I knew nothing of it, absolutely nothing.
What academic reputation did you think A&M had before you got here?
I had very, very limited contact with that.
We had a man came on our faculty at Iowa State in the fall of 1948.
named William Schweitzer, who graduated here in the spring of 48.
He was a classmate of George Shelton's.
He came up to the diagnostics laboratory, and he stayed the rest of his career.
He just retired.
When did he retire, Kim?
About a year ago, two years ago?
Stayed the rest of his career there.
And I don't know.
Any other man from Texas that came up there, and Bill Monlux, who was an Iowa State graduate, who was the one who sent me down here, came there after I graduated.
And his brother, Andrew Monlux, was on the microbiology faculty when I was a student.
And he eventually became the head of the Department of Pathology at Oklahoma A&M.
But they were Iowans.
They were born and raised in Algona, Iowa.
But Monlux taught here for several years after World War II.
describe getting settled into the community and how you and your family became a part of the community?
Where did you find a place to live?
We bought a house
that just had been finished on Glade Street.
There were three houses in a row over there.
And this was the last one that was empty.
And it was a four bedroom house and with four children.
That's what we needed.
It was open and available.
And to avoid moving twice or more, we took it.
Paid $20,000 for it.
And I lived there until 1982.
As far as getting into the community is concerned, it was just easy.
Children in school?
Yes.
Susan was a freshman in high school.
She was in a band and played in athletics.
Sarah was in second grade.
Yeah, it was in second grade.
The other two hadn't started school yet.
In the two that were in school, did you have the impression that the local school system was better than or equal to or less than what you had experienced elsewhere?
It was better than what we had at Auburn, much.
What about shopping?
The only place you went to shop was Townshire.
That was it.
You didn't shop in College Station for anything.
But we didn't go out of town to shop either.
We never went out of town.
Anything we needed we got either at Sears or I can't remember all the different places in Townshire.
And downtown Bryan, we did a lot of shopping in downtown Bryan.
That's where we did most of it.
Did you join a church?
Yes, we went to church at the Methodist Church.
We moved in here on a
Wednesday, I think it was that we went to church on Sunday, and we've been going there ever since.
A&M Methodist.
A&M Methodist.
In fact, there are only probably three or four people going to church there now that have been there as long as I have.
Ed Holdridge was there, and Fred Benson's wife, and E.J.
Dykstra Heiss's wife, and that's about it.
This is not part of the interview.
Is Mrs. Benson still living?
Oh, yes.
We see her every Sunday.
Is she still living?
I would say she's taking a real like to Kim.
Kim makes a point of seeing her.
Would she be in?
Oh, yes.
And she'd be thrilled to death.
She's a delightful lady.
She's a lovely lady.
that church in those days.
I'm sure parking wasn't a problem.
I don't know.
We just had one service.
But two years after I got here, they got into a bit of a ministerial struggle.
And that went on until 1970.
Then in 1971, James Branagh It has really .
church that it served the campus?
That was its intent.
But then the other churches in the area were there too.
The A&M Presbyterian was A&M but the Lutheran church they didn't use the same proximity.
In terms of
Who they were?
No, no.
Just about everybody in the congregation was associated with the university.
Most business people in the community went to Bryan.
They were members of First Methodist Church.
The only time I've ever been to a midnight yell practice was at a bowl game somewhere, and I can't remember where.
Oh, it was in Memphis.
First time we played at the Liberty Bowl in Memphis.
That's the only midnight yell practice I've ever been to.
Have you been to the Silver Taps?
No, I haven't.
She has, but I haven't.
That first fall, you must have gone to a football game.
Yes, went to every one of them.
What was the impression of an Aggie football game in those first years?
Of course, the fall of 65 was a tough fall.
But I enjoyed the games.
I thought that Gene Stallings really got everything he had out of those guys.
And of course, the game with Texas Thanksgiving Day in 65 was probably...
Maybe as exciting a game as we've ever had in the series, really.
That was the day of the famous lateral pass and the long pass to McLean.
And they were down 17 to nothing at the half, and then came back and beat us 21 to 17 in the second half.
But it was fun.
And then, of course, basketball.
1966 was extremely exciting.
John Beasley and Mattson, they made the games fun.
Probably of all the basketball games that I've seen here, the game with Houston that fall
When they had Chaney and, oh, the big guy who played for years in the pros, was a center.
He was a sophomore that year.
I can't think of his name now.
But A&M, I think, beat them 96 to 93 or something like that.
And that was just really exciting as any basketball game you could ever see.
Now, when did you get involved outside of the department in some of the campus activities?
I'll call them.
Well, I'm trying to remember which came first.
Probably in the summer of 1968, Buck Wirus

asked me to go to beaumont and speak to the beaumont a m club how did how did he know to call you well of course buck went to method church and uh i don't know i don't really know how that how the tie-in came but anyway i and i remember buck telling me on the way down he says no
I don't care what you say or how you say it, but... And it'll go.
And I did.
And about that same time was when I got involved in commencement.
In the summer of 1968...
Thank you.
What's up?
How many hours of preparation a spring commencement might have taken?
Upwards of fifty at least.
Did you literally say them out loud somewhere, practice them?
I read them silently.
I never did them out loud.
I read them silently.
But when we'd be on the stage at the commencement exercises, I would go through the list at least twice before I got up to read.
Any horror stories of losing the list?
